Below is a **complete, self‑contained example** that shows how you can expose the C++ iterator from *libpcapng* to OCaml.  
It contains

* the public OCaml interface (`pcapng.mli`) – the API that OCaml users will see,  
* the C/‑C++ glue (`pcapng_stubs.c`) – a tiny C++ file compiled with `ocamlc`/`ocamlopt`,  
* a short “how‑to‑compile” recipe, and  
* a tiny usage example.

Feel free to copy‑paste the two source files into a directory, adjust the include / library paths for your own `libpcapng` installation, and you will have a working binding that lets OCaml code run a user‑supplied callback for **every frame** that the C++ iterator yields – exactly the “per‑row” style you see in pandas/Polars.

---

## 1. The OCaml public interface – `pcapng.mli`

```ocaml
(*--------------------------------------------------------------------
   pcapng.mli – high‑level OCaml bindings for libpcapng
   --------------------------------------------------------------------*)

(** {1 Types} *)

(** A parsed network frame.  All fields are read‑only – they are
    freshly allocated for each callback invocation. *)
type frame = {
  ts_sec   : int;          (** Timestamp seconds since epoch *)
  ts_usec  : int;          (** Micro‑seconds part of the timestamp *)
  caplen   : int;          (** Number of bytes actually captured *)
  origlen  : int;          (** Original length of the packet on the wire *)
  data     : bytes;        (** Captured payload (exactly [caplen] bytes) *)
}

(** An opaque handle to a pcapng file.  Created by {!open_file} and
    closed automatically by the OCaml garbage collector. *)
type t

(** {1 Exceptions} *)

(** Raised when the underlying C++ library reports an error
    (e.g. file not found, corrupted file, etc.). *)
exception Error of string

(** {1 Basic operations} *)

(** Open a pcapng file for reading.  Raises {!Error} on failure. *)
val open_file : string -> t

(** Iterate over *all* frames in the file and invoke the supplied
    OCaml callback on each one.

    The callback is called **in the same thread** that performs the
    iteration, so it may raise an exception to abort the walk early.
    Any exception raised by the callback is propagated to the caller
    of {!iter}.

    The iteration stops when the underlying iterator reports EOF or
    when the callback raises.  The iterator is **not** reusable after
    a call to {!iter}; you must create a fresh [t] with {!open_file}
    if you need to walk the file again. *)
val iter : t -> (frame -> unit) -> unit

(** A low‑level alternative: fetch the next frame manually.  Returns
    [None] when the iterator is exhausted.  This function is useful
    when you want to drive the walk yourself (e.g. combine it with
    other OCaml control flow). *)
val next : t -> frame option

(** {1 Convenience helpers} *)

(** Count how many frames a file contains.  Implemented as a thin
    wrapper around {!iter}. *)
val count_frames : string -> int
```

*Design notes*

* The public type `frame` is a **plain OCaml record** – easy to pattern‑match on
  and cheap to allocate (a few words + a `bytes` buffer).  
* The opaque type `t` is a custom block that holds a pointer to the C++ iterator.
  It is finalised automatically so the underlying C++ object is destroyed
  when the OCaml value is collected.
* The only “stateful” operation is `iter`, which mirrors the typical
  Data‑Frame `map` / `apply` style: the user supplies a function
  `[frame -> unit]` that is executed for every row (frame).  If the user
  raises, the walk aborts and the exception propagates – exactly how
  pandas/Polars behave.
* A low‑level `next` is also provided for completeness; it can be used
  to build custom folds, streams, etc.

